{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519815"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:16:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:16:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13087"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13087"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.16,0.05,0.63,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5524"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110600"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5524"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92845"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"1939"},{"type":"tags","id":"2701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"12749"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41792"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110600"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old Indigenous man presents to his local hospital with a one week history of feeling progressively unwell, with fevers, a productive cough and some shortness of breath. Since yesterday, he has developed severe right sided chest pain, along with a headache and some double vision. He is generally in good health, other than a background of well-managed type 2 diabetes mellitus. He is an agricultural worker on a property in Arnhem Land.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 128/85 mmHg, pulse 90/min, temperature 38.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 17/min. He has loss of his left nasolabial fold and he is unable to raise his left eyebrow. He has no ophthalmoplegia and otherwise his cranial nerve exam is unremarkable. He has dullness to percussion on the right upper zone, with associated bronchial breathing. His heart sounds are dual with no murmurs\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is promptly treated with intravenous piperacillin-tazobactam and doxycycline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWithin four hours, the patient starts to slur his speech. His vital signs rapidly deteriorate, with a blood pressure of 91/65 mmHg, pulse 105/min, temperature 39.1\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 22/min.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is given IV meropenem. The patient thereafter shows signs of improvement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the patient\u0027s illness?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mycobacterium tuberculosis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Staphylococcus aureus","Burkholderia pseudomallei","Streptococcus pneumoniae"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is most likely to have infection due to \u003Cstrong\u003EBurkholderia pseudomallei\u003C/strong\u003E, the cause of melioidosis. This infection tends to have a very heterogenous presentation, and is often misdiagnosed; hence, it is sometimes referred to as \u0022the great mimicker.\u0022 This infection can have acute and chronic manifestations. It can cause upper lobe pneumonia - demonstrated in this patient\u0027s chest x-ray (as opposed to the lower lobe pneumonia typical of most microbes). Patients, when acutely infected, may have rapid deterioration that can lead to lethal septic shock. This microbe is unresponsive to most antibiotics, but can be treated with meropenem and/or ceftazidime. For these reasons, this infection has a high mortality rate.**\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for meliodosis are living in the Northern Territory, being Indigenous, having type 2 diabetes, and working in the outdoors (particularly in watery areas of the Northern Territory). Individuals with increased exposure to soil and water in endemic areas are at highest risk of infection, including Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples, agricultural workers, construction workers and ecotourists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient initially shows very general signs of infection that could be caused by a wide range of organisms. However, the fact that this patient is unresponsive to broad spectrum antibiotics indicates that this is unlikely to be \u003Cstrong\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae,\u003C/strong\u003E which is the most common cause of community acquired pneumonia, and is very infrequently resistant to empirical antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis \u003C/strong\u003Emay cause some of the symptoms shown, but is very unlikely to lead to rapid, acute deterioration, unless presenting in a patient with HIV co-infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no indication that this patient developed a hospital acquired infection or is immunocompromised, and so this is less likely to be \u003Cstrong\u003EStaphylococcus aureus. \u003C/strong\u003EIt normally responds to piperacillin-tazobactam.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs there is no indication of initially requiring a ventilator or having immunosuppresion, \u003Cstrong\u003EPseudomonas aeurginosa \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely. Furthermore, Pseudomonas aeurginosa is typically covered by piperacillin-tazobactam.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary manifestations of melioidosis vary between acute and chronic forms. In acute disease, imaging may show multiple small pulmonary nodules from haematogenous spread and multilobar consolidation, typically starting in the upper lobes. This can rapidly progress to cavitation or lung abscess formation. In subacute and chronic forms, radiological features are similar (mixed nodular or patchy opacities), though progression is slower in chronic cases. Complications include pneumothorax or hydropneumothorax from cavity rupture into the pleural space. Pleural effusions are uncommon and usually associated with lower lobe involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E**Twelve deaths were reported in the wet season in 2025 in Far North Queensland (The Australian).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Burkholderia pseudomallei, the cause of melioidosis, is a neglected infection that is often misdiagnosed but has a high mortality rate.","Risk factors for melioidosis are living in the Northern Territory and working in outdoor environments, having diabetes, and being Indigenous.","Treatment for melioidosis involves a 14 day regimen of meropenem and/or ceftazidime"],"references":["Harvey, J., Boles, B., \u0026 Brown, D. (2020). A review of imaging findings in melioidosis: revealing the tropics\u2019 dirty secret. Radiology of Infectious Diseases, 7(4), 176-185.","Chakravorty, A., \u0026 Heath, C. H. (2019). Melioidosis: an updated review. Australian journal of general practice, 48(5), 327-332.","Alsaif, H. S., \u0026 Venkatesh, S. K. (2016). Melioidosis: spectrum of radiological manifestations. Saudi Journal of Medicine \u0026 Medical Sciences, 4(2), 74","Bacterial disease claims 12 lives. The Australian 27/2/25","Campos, A. Melioidosis. Radiopaedia. Internet webpage. [cited March 2025]. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/melioidosis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92845"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13087"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20315"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20315"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wSrxlsXStZ3xEnXLvWhosAxZqR4ZJu.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/wSrxlsXStZ3xEnXLvWhosAxZqR4ZJu.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":514,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92845"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T08:48:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T08:50:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5524"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110600"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"desc